The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually old, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "become" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
“Men seldom suffer such a thing.”
“Healthy young women are also not isolated, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the state of West Africa, Burkina Faso takes care of a special residence of more than 100 women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure”.
It issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was caught in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease witch hunting, in Gambia last year the president still participated.
Gambian President Jammeh, following the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging hunt for witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from Gambian villages to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a pound of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive their stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs higher rent
The man, elderly and stout, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving sentence.
All three have just been caught in rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 CZK per month, the son will pay 4,100 CZK from next year onwards for a two-room apartment with a separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in the new contract of his son, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a move.
“Everyone says a thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major test laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up number.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a light button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a small piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for repairs, insurance issues, and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 flats belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," respond, after briefly hesitating, the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and former Bakala miner’s flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the vice-president of the Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, from Ostrava, from the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, already addressed them loud and clear, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my goddamn bathroom plate," the man mentioned in the introduction says.
According to the workers, for the moment, retirees come more than anything to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as the special offer of RPG promises.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the February rental discount.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked about the rent in 2011,” estimates the window clerk.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, an independent judge must settle the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible way to proceed and completely in accordance with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
“Nobody’s going to be judged here,” says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means of going to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
"The rental increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of CZK 7.50 per month per square meter," it says on the screen.
Only increased by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, 19.66 crowns per square meter," RPG said.
In 2,600 flats, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rents suddenly, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rental increase (see the graph) back into the floors, mainly in savings on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides in its interior a small nursery with all its own to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known buildings in Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-garden.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the daycare is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-childcare was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-childcare is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as the Czech State budget.
Thanks to the financing granted (more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-custody running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified personnel; a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The day-care centre currently accommodates children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guard", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is a matter of individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten programme are comparable to the regular pre-school programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach English.
The classroom has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can visit their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all of this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order are observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the window frames, railings, door trims, gazebos and signs.
Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, arose from the remodeling of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol took part in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá and Güell Park, where other pieces of it can be found.
Because of its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be odd.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the building norms of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked by the result that it asked for correction.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without having to give up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors brings maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage list.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious apartment and the most recharged of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open their doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
