Families will have to pay an additional expense of several hundred crowns per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to withdraw several hundred crowns a month from the portfolio from January onwards.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The increase in electricity for families living in apartments is expected to amount to about 100 crowns more per year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers lowered prices, as support for the production of energy from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas is moderately expensive, especially at a time when heating is used the most and, therefore, consumption is higher.
In this case, they should also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are expensive across the country, the price change of central heating varies from place to place.
The increase in prices is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 kroner per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay an additional 1,000 kroner per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to endure a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, the Pragueers will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will increase by 7.4%.
The prices of the rental of 450,000 apartments rented in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, can increase considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 apartments in <0xC3><0x9A>stí nad Labem, will increase rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court those who do not agree with the new rent.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase by as much as 10 percent next year.
Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in fashion, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause them to end up in medical care young drinkers under the age of fifteen.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome a hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
“Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk.”
"Fashion is now strong alcoholic beverages," says Pravo the head of pediatrics at Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelikán.
"When they manage to get their dad a bottle from the locker, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage that it lightens with juice and it doesn’t smell that much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's about Fernet or rum."
"Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
“In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home,” Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, thirteen- and fourteen-year-old drinkers usually appear in hospitals.
Before Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics at Motol, where ambulances were taking young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture with ecstasy," the department's doctor said.
"He was at the Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours," he said.
It is precisely the parents’ lack of interest or even their clear tolerance for drinking on the part of their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependence.
"An alcoholic is a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year at the pediatric clinic of Motol forty drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who go home with their parents or the police after a medical examination do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: Halloween, New Year's Day and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the start of the holidays."
“On Witches’ Day I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunken children at once,” adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"These are much better off, because after the hectic night, they get up well and don't hurt at all."
“They’re just confused about where they are,” Pelikán says, adding that patients often lose their sense of humor at least when they see the expenses they’ve incurred.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for severe patients can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
“I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a job for young people so that you would earn enough to pay for yourself that night,” adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his view, perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 jets found for the first time in foreign hands in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the aircraft Casa - EADS is located.
It is the first time such a device has been found in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
