According to Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, EADS has pledged that the aircraft will be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
“The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve for the practices of pilots from NATO countries.”
“It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this framework,” Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek says.
The newspaper Hospodá<0xC5><0x99>ské noviny published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defense did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159s overseas.
The Czech army has acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already sued the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by conducting a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
