The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in a number of countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a reduced 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a sharp decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but significantly higher than 25 per cent in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted their country ' s Congress and 45 per cent trusted their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has been maintained during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only marginally increased in 2009 and has declined again this year, to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent said they or a close relative had been a victim of crime in the past year, down from 38 per cent last year and the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chavez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
Elections to the Garbage
No one expected the general elections held on 28 November in Haiti to be perfect.
However, it was much worse than feared by foreigners trying to help the country recover from its problems.
Votes were introduced at the polls, some people voted several times, ballots thrown in the sewers, polling stations destroyed and acts of intimidation.
The electoral colleges opened with hours of delay.
Numerous Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, roamed the area trying to find out where they had to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, denounced fraud and called for the election to be annulled.
The protests, some of them violent, spread across the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the highest-ranking UN official in Haiti, said it was “a relatively good election in many ways.”
The observers for the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously affirmed that "we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, which according to its opponents is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and to his candidate, Jude Célestin, is expected to announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The tiebreaker is expected to take place in January.
Not all hopes have yet been lost in relation to the elections.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial petition requesting the invalidation of the vote.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr Célestin, who has hardly any support, if any, has passed the second round.
With the cholera epidemic ravaging the country and more than a million earthquake survivors still living in tents, a large abstention is expected.
At the time, many Haitians wanted to vote, but failed to do so due to a lack of organization.
Around 250,000 identity documents, required to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the election.
There's a lot at stake.
Aid donors consider the election of a legitimate people’s government to be an essential step in Haiti’s reconstruction.
And, as it has become clear, the Haitians themselves think so.
Advancing toe-to-toe towards the center
In the weeks since she lost her husband, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernandez, has enjoyed great public sympathy that has increased her popularity rate by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level she has recorded since her election in 2007.
Despite everything, whether she can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year’s election will depend on whether the clearly affected Ms. Fernandez leaves aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, was accustomed to drafting budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend the additional income at its discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernandez’s government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened since Kirchner’s death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the ruling Peronist movement have clashed with Ms. Fernandez.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore be applied to next year, which will give the President even more room for action when it comes to spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow as much as 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the wage demands of the unions, place it at about 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the verge of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, put pressure on the private sector and had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt the official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernandez moderate these policies now?
He has convened meetings between the private sector and trade union leaders.
In addition, its officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been driven by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the momentum for growth achieved with a major devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps this is why Mrs Fernandez is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina’s financial ties with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs Fernandez is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF oversight, as is usually the case.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems to be the prelude to the cleanup of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernandez wants to remain in politics after her term ends, given that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have waned.
If you want to win another election, you will have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of your husband’s policies.
