Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise choice in the category of Revelation Artist.
Act at the request of a president and possibly people will notice you.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old bassist and jazz singer personally selected by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, was one of the Grammys’ surprises this year with a top-notch nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist.
Considering that Spalding has been an acclaimed jazz figure since his 2008 album "Esperanza", the nomination is thought-provoking, but respects the Grammys rules that it must be an artist who has not released more than three albums before recording the one that "determines the public identity of that artist".
His ambitious 2010 album "Chamber Music Society" was undoubtedly a breakthrough and, given his light and pleasant vocal style, as well as a great skill with pop, funk and Latin rhythm influences, one can at least draw a distinction between Spalding and the path to success of Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammys voters, who have lately focused on jazz.
In the remaining categories, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio’s “Historicity,” an exciting and magnificent record that was a favorite last year.
Among Iyer's competitors are veteran saxophonist James Moody with "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley for "Positootly."
Trombone Shorty, a roaring New Orleans favorite and regular guest on HBO's "Treme," was honored in the contemporary jazz category, which otherwise leans considerably towards fusion as on the albums of Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Darcy’s wild punk James Argue’s Secret Society earned well-deserved recognition in the big band category, competing against the great chamber jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the ever-risking Dave Holland, whose live album with his octet, “Pathways,” was a great example of the bassist’s democratic leadership in his band.
Grammy Award Nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey for Best Director of Classical Albums
Classical music nominations for the 53rd Grammy Awards include a mix of musicians and composers from around the world.
The top nominations were for Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", for piano and orchestra, five-movement, and Steve Mackey for "Dreamhouse", an eclectic three-movement orchestral work.
Nominees with links to Southern California include Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
Classical music nominations are distributed in thirteen categories spanning orchestral, opera, choral and solo albums.
The Classic Producer of the Year category includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the Classical Music album are Bruckner for Symphonies No. 3 and No. 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Castri and Synergy Vocals; the "Sacrificium" of the Choquificium.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" by the Royal Opera House orchestra; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio and Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the National Orchestra; and Marinsky's "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the Orchestra.
Grammy-nominated composers for contemporary compositions include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Passionately Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, about 30 minutes long, is nicknamed “Los Angeles” and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" is nominated for instrumental solo performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for him to play on mandolin Avi Avital, who performed the concert with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"He composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms from North Africa," Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated in the orchestral function category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Nominated instrumental soloists include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees as vocal soloists are all women this year: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classic mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song."
