Promoting a more moderate side of maintaining order in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the pass in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, the corpulent policemen of China’s urban order, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"First!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely passed their teens in white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed above the hair tied with blue and white striped buns.
"Personally, I think they look normal," Mr. Tang said, contemptuously.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a bachelor's degree.
Guangdong Province changed the uniforms' grayish green color to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a tricky snack cart, and watched it with a constantly frown for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s tiny respect for these squads of the city.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after using his cellphone to film them as they disbanded a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted on the internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without making them bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a brawl with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded “really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered if the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district notice called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure “and the five harmonious facial features.”
They must have been above average height, above 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Withdrawal at the age of 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the job was physically too hard for women over the age of 25.
“His image is the important thing,” an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
“First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc.”
Then comes the temperament "and inner qualities."
The female chengguan are like vases, he said, adding, "in addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district’s city administration office, is not eager to back up that description.
But he noted that height requirements were standard on many Chinese job postings for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If this means being handsome, it is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the disabled or disfigured should not present themselves.
“We can’t allow a lame person or a humpback to come to work here,” Mr. Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be right."
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his red cheeks and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn’t think the accent on her appearance is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" he asked with a sardonic look.
His fellow dimple worker, 21-year-old Xu Yang, said "Our work must present the image of the city."
They also don’t object to their time-bound work, they said, because they harbor greater career ambitions than simply chasing salespeople into the alleys where they’re supposed to circumscribe their business.
Every morning, the squad faces roughly a dozen street vendors who throw themselves on foot or by bike, trying to sell as many buns or bowls of tofu as possible before they are thrown out.
"Mr. Wang, you have to go."
“We’ve told you so many times!” said Miss Xu as a salesman ran off on foot, temporarily abandoning his bicycle-drawn cart with noodle trims.
Officers describe their duties as more monotonous than exhausting.
“This is pretty much the same every day,” said Huang Jing, 20, who studies marketing in his spare hours.
“Very routine.”
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate the merchandise from the sellers.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from sudden public displays of animosity against bureaucracy, which are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the provincial capital of Yunnan, mutinied after false rumors spread that some chengguan officers had killed a salesman.
More than a dozen police or chengguan officers were injured in the night episode; 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
For the time being, Xindu has avoided such violence.
Calm is barely guaranteed.
Just two blocks from peaceful Baoguang Square, where female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered in a corner.
Officers had confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk rather than in a workshop, as required by the regulations.
The owner of the motorcycle screamed loudly.
The situation stalled for 15 minutes before the officers, with a bad face, made their way to their vehicles and quickly left with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator assigned to the men’s squad, remained behind, with his white badge turned around to hide his name.
Like female officers, coordinators, men aged 40 and over, play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not taught to maintain an elegant image.
"Sometimes we fight verbally."
“Sometimes we fight physically,” Mr. Li said quite naturally.
“Most of the time it’s the audience that starts the fight.”
Prosecutors will not bring charges against Senator Ensign
The senator’s attorneys announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have acquitted Senator John Ensign of criminal charges stemming from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure lobbying work for the woman’s husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it was "certainly pleased" with the decision, which came after a year-long investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of his investigation and that he has no plan to bring charges against him on this issue.”
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have colluded to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, obtain lucrative lobbying work to silence Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as the treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign assistant, he was excluded under the law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban," which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, “it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens amid procedural misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s top lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another phone call the next day, telling him the department did not want to file charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave prosecutors.
“I don’t feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to show that the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got work through lobbying thanks to Ensign’s help to Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him he was "crushing" the Home Office over a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a luncheon with Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and called the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair first surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, she said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department’s lead and conclude its investigation.
“Senator Ensign is eager to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada,” he said.
Cheshire appeal will target Twitter
There were half a dozen of them “chatting” in the ranks of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the appalling testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a family from Cheshire, Connecticut, is set to come to an official end, with the imposition of the death penalty judge voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed court papers outlining the arguments for appeals that are likely to occupy the courts for years to come.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reports about the process, including widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “a circus atmosphere,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details caused public passions to exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appellate judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“Based on what I experienced during this trial, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of new technology in the courtroom is affecting the individual’s rights to have a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, Hayes’ senior defense attorney.
Trial Judge Jon C. Blue of the State Superior Court laconically dismissed the lawsuits in a ruling last week, saying the news media were “carefully controlled” and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But it probably won’t be the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that coverage of celebrity cases can raise questions about the impartiality of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in its decision, in the Sheppard v. Maxwell case, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
The crime is believed to have been inspired by the television program and the movie "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said the appeals courts that examined Mr. Hayes’s conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the form of communication from courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There is a general cause for concern about the impact of new media” on high-profile processes, said John J. Donohue III, a Stanford Law School professor who studied the Connecticut death penalty and wrote a report saying it was arbitrarily imposed.
Professor Donohue said some appellate judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make trials fairer.
The Twitter issue is just one of many topics outlined by Hayes’ lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying an execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes could have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors, showing them creepy photographs of the crime scene during jury selection.
Some jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pushed for a verdict for his bizarre decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But his arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process may attract most interest.
They noted in a rebuttal to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually firewood the fire of emotion over the case.
“The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom,” the lawyers wrote, “was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps across the state.”
Their focus on Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said the complaint that immediate news was more important than reports delivered more slowly was a ludicrous view that would make the court’s policy on controlling coverage weak in future lawsuits.
But some lawyers said appeals courts were often drawn to arguments about the adaptation that was required in court due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their letter, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which overturned Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to the coverage of the process, and made it clear that they would demand that the new media require new rules.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case of the 21st century.”
Can civics build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, this week has unleashed some civility in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues that need to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But by what everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion of the two parties’ differences, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to win partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilized, despite the political differences that persist among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep-rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
Elections awaken partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of it.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, there is likely to be a commitment to expanding unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t make people believe they’re in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about whether civics can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health care law.
Those lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase of some taxes and the retirement age, and the cut in expenditures.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been tasked with one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly brought the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will come in the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch closely the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they’re losing will likely change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partidism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as paradise of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” leaving a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly from the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has termed the “vertical authority,” takes its share as money climbs the ladder.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he claimed: "It's crazy, a mess, a nuisance."
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, since they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
“The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional’, and to claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government,” the statement said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal and mafia world that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that runs through the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government bureaucracy.
“Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in Moscow’s criminal world.”
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
“Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS collects money from larger companies, and that the police are targeting small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, the protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their businesses closed for one reason or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The note from the embassy reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem group of experts in Moscow, said in a recent interview.
“But he’s a part of this bureaucracy.”
“He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154 (countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. embassy note, which did not happen until late at night Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and although Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested the WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation claiming that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we don’t suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and cared about his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as “the Butcher” for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint United Nations and Cambodia court issued the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Yev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of those events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can’t do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
“For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is creating divisions within families.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government led by Pol Pot, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the utter misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
“These people have received little benefit after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They have incorporated the regime’s utopian agrarian ideology.”
“They were raised without any concept for doing business.”
Sr. Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
“But now life is hard because we have to self-supply.”
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concerns here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute the top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This didn't do much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at Cambodia’s Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
During a recent embarrassing afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his house on wooden piles on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She said that if the court summoned her, she would not appear.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” he said.
“If there is more prosecution, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court prosecutes more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to the Khmer, is to bring the broken pieces back together," he said.
“It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea," of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered in discarded plastic bags leads to a black soot rectangle covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
