Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole of the Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or suppression of the 426 euros of aid to the unemployed without benefit, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, of the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and of 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Keep in mind that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, composed of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for offending countries, possible suspensions of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defining itself for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government pulled out of its sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed needed to be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painstakingly extended the decision to rescue Greece.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel emerges again with a clear position, demanding reform of the EU treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should assist in the process of reforming the Union that will make those measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we have to take action now with which he may not agree very much, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which offending countries will be severely punished, may be forced to declare suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is telling us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, simply will not tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand from us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquility.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity that they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with the big companies and the announcement of new measures yesterday) suggests that, despite the criticism of Merkel, the thesis that we must put order at home has opened its way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it does not seem to be moving.
And, among the possibilities contemplated, the possibility of leaving a monetary area too crowded with less serious countries cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it has already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Jokes like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not willingness to escape a penalty.
The expulsion allegedly wrought by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with only a few minutes left to finish the match (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when it came to taking out fouls to provoke the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction in the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clear of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different amounts of money for the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which in past times has fined its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud of law; for, indeed, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but they seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that comprises the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods to which fair play is alluded is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They awaited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another issue is what kind of advantage infringers gain in the intentional misconducts examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that it is not placed in a disadvantageous situation to the opponent nor profit is obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action implies leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of uncertainty, because the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty match and move on to the second card cycle, in which the suspension for card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, from going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the enforcement of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because they were two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them took place.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
