Pakistan's nuclear program raises concern in U.S.
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at “a faster rate than any other country.”
WikiLeaks leaks confirm ties between Taliban and Pakistan
The content of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns caused in Washington by the Pakistani nuclear program.
Aside from the enlightening and juicy details they offer about the content of the talks and the thoughts of U.S. diplomatic representatives accredited to Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on atomic security, instead of increasing, "decreases," and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for the unrest in Washington.
The Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, said in a report prior to the visit of then-National Security Adviser James Jones: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersal of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials.”
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is considered, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as a proliferating and reason to keep watch.
“Pakistan has had to hire people with strict religious beliefs to protect the nuclear facilities; given the drop in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs,” Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The newest piece of documentation leaked by Julian Assange’s website is the growing decline in U.S.-Pakistan cooperation on nuclear proliferation issues and Pakistan’s high rate of nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, calling communication with Pakistan “frustrating,” said: “Transparency is often non-existent; aid offers remain unanswered or are discarded.”
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Patterson also calls on Washington, during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make “very clear” to the official that “the Pakistan Army must end tacit support for terrorist groups.”
