Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it is difficult to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a “red alert” to “locate and follow the movements” of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
It’s not new, it’s dated November 20th.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million U.S. diplomatic documents but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
WikiLeaks founder Mark Stephens said: “The police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.
It was on the 20th when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
As things stand, all 188 Interpol countries have indications of identifying or locating Assange “with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition.”
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries do consider the so-called free-way notice network to proceed with an arrest — which must be made by the national police force — especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move has outraged Assange’s lawyers, who published a letter yesterday denouncing that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder has been willing to respond by videoconference to questions from Swedish authorities.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, which they compare to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s security chief.
"This looks like a hunt, not a legal pursuit," the letter said.
As the world searches for him - and from Australia his mother defends the innocence of his son - Assange remains unknown, but not silent.
On Monday, he granted an interview to the director of Time magazine via Skype from an undetermined location, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering U.S. diplomats to spy on the U.N. in violation of international treaties that the U.S. has signed, he should resign," he said.
