China maintains goals to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that he supports his offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its emission of greenhouse gases.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, China’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to convert its industry.
In fact, he said, in the last four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programs.
In all those areas, progress has been made, including the approval last year of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with state and local authorities, to achieve the goals of energy saving, energy efficient use and reduction of emissions.
In addition, several multi-annual plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, are in progress or have already been concluded.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficient Program, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent spotlights to savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific advisor on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent over the past five years and expects to do the same by 2020.
