From Tuesday to Wednesday night, several regions recorded heavy rainfall, between 40 and 70 millimeters of rain.
An additional 20 to 40 millimeters are also expected from now until Thursday night, depending on the region.
The sectors north of the river and in the Outaouais valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to a total of 100 millimeters of rain.
Given that these precipitations add to the snow melt that had already accumulated in certain sectors, it is feared that several rivers will overflow.
On Wednesday night, Quebec’s Civil Security unit issued alerts for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in Lanaudière.
The rivers of the north, in Saint-Jérôme, in the Laurentians, and the Chêne, in Lotbinière, have already caused flooding in the past and are under surveillance.
