It's partly Dupont's fault.
Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont has suffered a setback before the Canadian Radio-television Standards Council (CCNR) for controversial statements regarding welfare and Haitians, as well as for his rude language on the radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr. Dupont and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained "inaccurate information about social assistance, an unduly negative representation of Haitians and rude language that should not be used in the broadcasts broadcast during the day".
The Council has also indicated that discussions on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two people who had committed suicide, do not infringe the broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints regarding comments made on broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision came after a complaint from the Common Front of People Receiving Social Welfare from Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the issue were not correct.
Presenters should provide reliable data, not misleading ones.
In connection with the suicide, the present Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most members of the Committee have concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be considered as a solution to life ' s problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes in question of 'Dupont le midi' have dealt with a sensitive issue in an equitable and appropriate manner."
Any guilt has therefore been discarded in this regard.
The latest litigation concerned statements made after the earthquake in Haiti.
At that time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had been the protagonists of a media confrontation that had provoked numerous reactions.
The CHOI presenter stated that he had made no donation to help the Haitians because he could not know for sure if the needy would actually receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension up there."
“My file has been clean for a year and a half,” the presenter said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the use of gross language.
In any case, the radio station CHOI-FM has collaborated "even more than required".
The consequences will be minimal for the broadcaster, which must, among other things, announce the decisions once in the hours of greatest hearing within three days.
A kung-fu king in Montreal
The Algerian-born Montrealer Nacereddine Zemmal has had an extremely peculiar journey.
The athlete, who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and and Thai boxing, climbs the tatami and rings of the world in search of new challenges.
“I started practicing martial arts like kung-fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria,” said Zemmal, who has lived in the metropolis since 2008 to advance the professional level.
“In my case, I look for fights everywhere because, for those who don’t enjoy playing on the ground involving mixed martial arts, there are few competitions in North America.”
The athlete, who works as a security officer and as an employee of the UPS company, has recently given bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) Amateur World Championships, held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
“I’ve won in the full contact kickboxing and Thai boxing categories,” he explained.
"I am currently preparing to participate in the San Shou World Cup in China."
“They will invite athletes who have finished in the top four in the last world championship in each category.”
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto."
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished in eighth place."
"In 2007, in China, I finished the tournament in fifth place, but I reached third place in Toronto in 2009."
"The interesting thing is that I have progressed in every competition."
"At this stage, I'll be the first this time or next year!"
The "san shou" or "sanda" is a discipline originating in China in which it is allowed to strike with fists and feet, as well as to throw opponents to the ground.
Clashes are originally held on a platform and, less frequently, in a ring.
The most famous boxer in this type of combat is the American of Vietnamese origin Cung Le, widely recognized in the world of martial arts.
Although Nacer Zemmal should only keep one competition in his career, he will certainly attend the great "King of Sanda" tournament, the Super Bowl of kung-fu.
“This competition is the most notorious and prestigious in China,” explains the friendly boy.
“It’s like the equivalent of the Lumpinee stadium (the largest stadium in Thailand).”
"It's been an incredible experience."
Zemmal has won his first match, in the semifinals of his category (80 kg), but lost in the final.
“The one who has won me is a real professional,” he says.
"There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"The winners of the semi-finals face each other in the final of their category."
"Then the champions of each category face off to crown a single champion, the king of kung-fu."
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has awarded direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than one hundred contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a previous tender the most important contract, the project management, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie gestion, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec’s decision to entrust the private sector with the responsibility of managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
At the beginning of 2005, the Énergie gestion consortium obtained the lucrative contract without a prior public tender.
For the Quebec Party, the use of business consortia poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and cause prices to rise.
“This is a new method of collusion and eliminating competition.”
"That is, people, instead of doing it in secret, now do it openly," Quebec Party deputy Sylvain Simard told a news conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can be benefited in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that there had been any collusion with this contract.
"I'm starting to get tired," he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted in a "dishonest" and "lack of rigour."
He pointed out that "the minimum" would be for the PQ to apologize.
The formula of consortia is a common practice throughout the world.
Typically, it is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already begun and will last until 2012.
In any event, the contract was awarded without competition; it was a negotiation.
In addition, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the norm in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the consortium formula in the technical advisory sector is being investigated by the government.
A quick look at Quebec’s trade register allows you to identify more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Genivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, namely Dessau.
Regarding the Énergie gestion consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the James Bay territory responds to a particular labor dynamic and Hydro-Québec has been responding specifically to it since the 1970s."
The great head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation that has highlighted the fact that the project management contract has been awarded directly.
“If you respond to a bid and there are few participants, your prices are going to be higher.”
“You have two options: you can get in touch with the players in the sector and tell them: we are going to negotiate a satisfactory agreement and at a good price.”
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of the people," Laporte said.
The contract awarded to the Énergie gestion consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir has identified 109 technical advisory contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has obtained 22 contracts, Génivar obtained 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its participation in Énergie gestion.
All contracts were negotiated.
In total, they amount to $449,783,344, including the Énergie gestion contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has hinted that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "good acquaintances of the Quebec Liberal Party."
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "finance" it, before specifying that it is more about its leaders.
Barometer of responsible consumption. The "green" label does not inspire confidence
More ecological, but deeply skeptical.
Quebec consumers barely rely on sustainable development actors, fair trade brands and ecological certificates to guide their choices.
According to the Barometer of Responsible Consumption, whose first results were published yesterday, the situation is even worse. The consumer is immersed in a media universe where messages that defend a more responsible consumption are plentiful, but regrets the lack of reliable information and considers that this even slows their commitment.
Even if consumption of so-called “socially responsible” products has increased in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two-thirds of them say, in fact, that they do not trust the environmental commitment of companies or the environmental advertising of them, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatory of Responsible Consumption of the University of Sherbrooke.
Another conclusion: half of consumers question the reliability of official certificates bearing the so-called fair products, as well as the credibility of products and brands bearing labels indicating that they are "ecorresponsible", the Barometer notes.
Similarly, only 14.6% of Quebecers take politicians’ speeches on this issue seriously.
In any case, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this consumption sector, which is currently supported by about a third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, gaps and the dubious nature of the information cause 46% of consumers to discard this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers say they are also suspicious of the supposed yields of the ecological products or services they are trying to sell.
On the other hand, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their convictions.
61% have given priority to shopping in their neighborhood stores and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, the Barometer notes.
Greener and more responsible (the index of responsible consumption has reached 64 points out of a maximum of one hundred this year), Quebec’s Homo consumus loves to take the place of the king of recycling who tries to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of wildlife.
However, according to the Barometer, that social awareness seems to be out of doors: in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers indicated that they used public transport or shared cars to defend their environmental principles.
In addition, 39.1% of the participants in this comprehensive behavior survey, which has just completed its first edition, support the use of bicycles and walking.
