A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the global car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that amount should still be decreased to stabilize, before 2020, the rise in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from spiraling out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of compact fluorescent light bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced even more.
Compact fluorescent light bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above all, they contain no mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent compact light bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not compact fluorescent light bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted with incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the benefits that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
Ivory Coast eagerly awaits announcement of election results
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has called for the "immediate" publication of the results of the presidential elections in Ivory Coast, given that the deadlines have expired.
“The Secretary-General stresses the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and announce the provisional results immediately,” a spokesman for the UN chief said.
“Calls on all Ivorian parties and institutions to demonstrate their sense of responsibility and refrain from any initiative until the provisional results are announced.”
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has allowed Wednesday's deadline to pass at midnight without the results being published, three days after Sunday's scrutiny.
About forty minutes before the deadline, the CIS president had commented to television that the commission "continued working" to announce the results.
On Wednesday, demands for the CIS to finally proclaim the name of the winner of the second round between outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and his opponent Alassane Ouattara multiplied around the world.
However, Gbagbo’s side counts on the Constitutional Council’s annulment of the “fraudulent” votes in the north, in the hands of the former New Forces (NF) rebellion since the failed September 2002 coup d’état.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, campaign manager for the president of Ivory Coast, has said that the intimidation of voters carried out by the FN in the north of the country had deterred supporters of the outgoing president from going to vote.
The entire election could be annulled if the Constitutional Council accepts Gbagbo’s complaints.
However, Gbagbo’s opponents consider that the country’s highest court is not neutral, as it is headed by Paul Yao N’Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a man from the north who denies any relationship with the former rebels, has deemed “unacceptable” the delay in the publication of the results and has asked Gbagbo to respect them, but has not gone so far as to claim victory.
