Unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3% on mainland territory (9.7% taking into account the overseas departments), as indicated by the data corrected with the provisional seasonal variations (CVE) published on Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed remains at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
The data for the second quarter have been confirmed, 9.3% of the working population in mainland territory and 9.7% with the DOM.
In a year, the unemployment rate has increased by 0.1 points.
Overall, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter, but want to work, whether or not they are available within two weeks to work and whether or not they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has continued to worsen, with the unemployment rate rising again to 24.2% in mainland France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year), 25% including the DOM.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed according to the ILO.
For its part, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among the elderly, up to 6.4% in mainland France (+0.2 points in both three months and one year), i.e. 482,000 people over 50 years, a figure that amounts to 6.6% with the DOM.
There has only been a stability of unemployment among people aged between 25 and 49 years, with 8.3% in mainland France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% in the whole of France.
The INSEE has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, following a controversy over its calculation methods.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistical agency, continues to do so and on Tuesday announced a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October, after 9.9% in September.
