Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” US revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for novelties about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The whistleblower is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what do I know, editor of Libération), who considers only what he can recognize to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sending the U.S. embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same that Newsweek published the week before.
So why have the revelations of these records caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every educated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since the Second World War and since the Heads of States can call each other by phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer who watches research films knows it perfectly well, we just pretend that we don’t know it by hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker could consult the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country greatly affects the State Department’s prestige.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the " executioners ".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in the time of Orwell, he could be conceived at all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put on the net any confidential information, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also clear that, with today’s technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a science fiction thing and, therefore, novelistic, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with (telephone) wires.
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of montage, while now CDs (digital) only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With the high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the commutes that it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being secretly plotted in embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s hustle and bustle in its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the fast-start or early-start pledges made by developed countries have been met.
And the French chapuces have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation turned out to be appreciable and was appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and $150 million is added in three years in terms of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while claiming to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no norm and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that every euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document for your own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
It's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term detail of the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
