Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value given the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the food that a child of about ten years consumes in four meals and one snack a day.
These model meals, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"While in virtually all cases the legal limits for each chemical are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the slice of salmon was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “contaminant cocktails” generate for the consumer “is likely to be underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
